   <text>
      <body>
         <div type="letter">
            <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB1232_1824_10_24_page01.jpg"/>
            <opener>
               <dateline>
                  <date when="1824-10-24"/>Oct<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 24<hi rend="superscript">h</hi>. 1824<lb/>
               </dateline>
               <salute>My dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauF1">Francis</persName>
                  <lb/>
               </salute>
            </opener>
            <p> 
               You could not have given<lb/>
               me a better proof of your<lb/>
               wish &amp; power to serve me<lb/>
               than the sheet you sent<lb/>
               me revised - I thank you<lb/>
               &amp; I wish the size of my thank<lb/>
               you could convey the<lb/>
               warmth of the feeling</p>
            <lb/>
            <p>I have profited by all<lb/>
               your &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName>s corrections<lb/>
               and suggestions - I agree<lb/>
               with your principle <choice>
                  <orig>res-<lb/>
                  pecting</orig>
                  <reg>respecting</reg>
               </choice> technical terms -<lb/>
               I wonder that <persName ref="./Personography.xml#MarcX1">M<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. Marcel</persName>
               <lb/>
               <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Paris_FR">Paris</placeName>
               <lb/>
               <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB1232_1824_10_24_page02.jpg"/>
               
               &amp; <persName ref="./Personography.xml#WedgJ1">
                  <add>Jos</add> Wedgewood</persName> both good<lb/>
               chemists let these<lb/>
               pages pass without<lb/>
               observation - But<lb/>
               their interest in the<lb/>
               affair is not as strong<lb/>
               as yours.<lb/>
               Pray in future spare<lb/>
               yourself the trouble<lb/>
               of so fully illustrating<lb/>
               and illuminating<lb/>
               your observations my<lb/>
               dear friend - This is<lb/>
               loves labour lost with<lb/>
               me for I assure you<lb/>
               I am not attached<lb/>
               <pb n="3" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB1232_1824_10_24_page03.jpg"/>
               
               to my errors &amp; have<lb/>
               no affection for my<lb/>
               own sentences -<lb/>
               When I spoke of the<lb/>
               awe I felt for your<lb/>
               criticism &amp; its <choice>
                  <orig>depress<lb/>
                  ing</orig>
                  <reg>depressing</reg>
               </choice> effect on my mind<lb/>
               that related only to the<lb/>
               effect while I was<lb/>
               <pb n="4" facs="Edgeworth_Huntington_FB1232_1824_10_24_page04.jpg"/>
               
               only to save my friends<lb/>
               the trouble of them<lb/>
               not to be <add>
                  <unclear>so</unclear>
               </add> ungrateful<lb/>
               as to depreciate their<lb/>
               labor - How very kind<lb/>
               it was of my dear <persName ref="./Personography.xml#BeauH1">Honora</persName>
               <lb/>
               to read &amp; correct that<lb/>
               sheet before she went<lb/>
               to bed the night<lb/>
            </p>
            <lb/>
         </div>
